If You don't have printer and You want to Purchase My designed parts You can contact this people:

Stef from United Kingdom - [email protected]

Parts are designed to be easy to print and assembly :)
If You want to print anything else just ask theme :)

In this moment My designs are:

Rear bumper with lights and hook (little hard to print and noone confirm this work)
Leaf springs (in progress)

There is group where I will post all designs for WPL and also wil ask for other designers to post their parts:
https://www.thingiverse.com/groups/wpl-rcs/things

WARNING !!
Due to problems with my printer I can't check all versions but i did just modify one that i printed and make some upgrades.

Here is a movie how i mounted it:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JCrRM-2kocg

So this is rear bumper in 4 versions for WPL B-1 and i think for other similar like Heng Long
One on picture is version for my hook from this link:
https://www.banggood.com/Yeah-Racing-Adjustable-Drop-Hitch-Black-110-RC-Car-Crawler-Off-Road-YA-0428-p-1184757.html?p=5G2717320323201310AJ

I try my best to make it easy to print and base and cover is easy to print but main part i did print 4th times before my printer did it but that's problem with my printer
problem in printing is in light's there is part that is in air attached only to walls (depending on lamp type)
I split design in 3 and 4 parts (depending on version) so it will make it easy to print.
There are two types of lamps. One is for cut version of 5mm LED that is shorter and second for full normal 5mm LED

CAUTION !!
I changed hole fro LED from 5mm to 5.2mm and You still may have problem to fit LED in there so be aware of that, You may need to drill or do something to file that hole !!
This may depend on accuracy of Your printer but i did enlarge all holes where part's go inside for about 0,2mm so now may be better and for me on normal sizes i needed to file most of parts and I don't need screws to hold it :D

You can mix parts except of hook attachment for normal mount that one will only work on dedicated version with two LED types

Like always i use 2mm screws. I did not find way to make easy to print hook so on pictures You will find that I used 2mm screw but You may edit it as You need.

I did post STL showing assembled versions and STL with lamps only so You can use it to make Your own bumper as You need

Take some time to check all versions and edit it as You wont it to be. I did what i could to make it work but I'm just a human and there may be some mistakes.
If You have any suggestions You may type to me and i will try to change it.

description.text:
W6 Overlock Auffangbehälter
Have fun GIRLS

Der Behälter besteht aus dem Grundelement und dem Seitenteil das links an die Maschine kommt. Und der Gnubbel hinten der in der Einbuchtung der W6 kommt.

Zusammenbau:
Die Teile werden im ausgebautem Zustand zusammengeklebt, z.B. mit Heißkleber.
Die besten Passung erhält man, wenn man den Gnubbel als Einzelteil in die dafür vorgesehen Öffnung legt und einen tropfen Heißkleber an der Stelle macht, wo der Gnubbel (Back.stl) an das Haupteil(Boddy.stl) angeklebt wird. Anschließend wird der Behälter eingerastet und an den Gnubbel mit noch heißem Kleber angepresst/angeklebt.

Ich würde mich sehr darüber freuen wenn ihr Bilder von euren fertigen Behältern hier einstellt.

title: Bottom and landing gear for Robocat 270

description.text:
I decided to assemble the frame Robocat 270 not as intended. I used the flight controller Omnibus F4 v3 pro (without current sensor) and PDB/ESC board BS430. But the simultaneous installation of these boards on the frame Robocat 270 is not provided. I installed the PDB board in the designated place and the flight controller I installed on the back side at the bottom (see photo). To protect the flight controller I made a model of bottom case. At the same time I decided to fix the landing gears on it. To fix the bottom case, you must move the four threaded pillars to the opposite side. This kind of assembly at the same time facilitates the dismantling of the frame for access to the boards separately. Through the holes at the bottom of the landing gear it is possible to pass carbon tubes with OD 3 mm. Together with the flight controller I also plan to place a compass board and RC receiver Radiolink R12DSM.

Project files for SketchUp Pro 2018 is attached.

Used together with motor protection from here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2655174
and wire protection from here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2656924

title: Orange Tip for Lancer Tactical SR-3 VIKHR Whirlwind

description.text:
Replacement Orange Tip for Lancer Tactical SR-3 VIKHR "Whirlwind".

My friend broke his so I designed a replacement. The original tip was threaded into the larger outer barrel and held by two pins. To my knowledge these pins hold the tip in place along with glue at the threading since in the US the orange tip is NOT supposed to be removed. I received the gun with the two pins bent upward. Using pliers I pushed the pins out and removed them entirely. Since printers are not all capable of printing precise threading I avoided designing threads to secure the tip so instead I cut out two 3mm holes which should line up with the two holes on the outer barrel. Using M3 screws you can secure the tip.

title: Dremel Flex Shaft Mill Adapter for LulzBot Taz

description.text:
This is a redesign inspired by solarnetone's holder. It prints without support but does require a few cap-head screws & nuts.

But you probably shouldn't do this!

  • The tip of an extruder nozzle exerts almost no torque on the carriage. The end of a milling tool, however, can act as a lever exerting significant torque on the carriage and rails. The machine has no way of sensing this and will happily destroy itself. You can also easily drive a cutting tool into your print bed.
  • It supports a very limited number of appropriate bits.
  • The Flex Shaft may not be suitable for continuous operation.
  • It creates a lot of vibration.
  • It's incredibly noisy.
  • You will have to manually modify your gcode because the TAZ is not a CNC mill.

At best I think you could do some basic engraving or cutting of circuit boards. Actually trying to mill out lots of material will probably bend the x-axis rods or wreak some other havoc.

Here's a video of it "working," obviously with poor speed/feed settings:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qORseHfmFGQ

After the nylon line, the next point of weakness in retracting badge holders are the vinyl straps. They either tend to rip due to cold weather and UV exposure, break due to hanging two or more badges, or the snap-fasteners become deformed.
This thing is used to replace that strap. It can hold two badges, and can fit most of the split-rings that are on most retractable badge holders.
I'll try to update the Badge Ring so that it will snap into place and not slide off the holder too easily. Update: Sorry I haven't uploaded a rotated version of the strap replacement, but like most others, I've been busy! However I have a hint... for those that are saavy with OpenSCAD, you can create a "Badge Ring" that is nice and long... I was initially trying to figure out a detente system in which the ring won't slip off the badge holder, but if the ring is "tall" enough, it should keep itself positioned between your badges and the retracting reel. When you need to replace the badge, you just pull the badges until enough wire is expose to the slide the ring up so that the badges can slip out.

This item should print sideways. You may want to rotate it 90 degrees on the Y-axis before slicing.
To install:
1: Find the small split ring at the end of your retractable badge holder.
2: Pry it open with two pliers and remove the old vinyl strap.
3: Replace the strap with the Thing.
4: Re-install the split ring on the retractable badge holder.
5: Slide the Badge Ring up to the split ring.
6: Pull one of the flat planks away from the body. It should hinge outward.
7: Thread that plank through the hole where the vinyl strap used to go for your badge.
8: Repeat with your second badge (on the other plank) if necessary.
9: Slide down the Badge Ring to keep the planks closed.

To attach the bracket you need one of the spare t-nuts given by Tevo an one 15mm M5 allen screw with a washer. Based on your printer calibration the bracket should fit smoothly. Make sure the brace not colliding with the silikon heat bed. Otherwise you must relevel the bed a little bit higher.

title: Fish tank powered water scrubber and current generator

description.text:
This is designed to remove physical media from the aquarium water. requires purchase of a pump, two suction cups and quilt batting. the adapters I made to hook into a vinyl tube are for an aquatop pump.
Instructions

  1. install the print labeled intake body to a length of vinyl tubing
  2. cut a square of quilt batting approx 4 inches x 4 inches.
  3. fold quilt batting in half twice.
  4. cut hole in center of quilt batting about the size of a pencil.
  5. insert the quilt batting over the center post of the intake body and tuck excess inside
  6. take a cover nut and the intake lid fasten the lid down making sure to tuck in all the quilt batting.
  7. install a suction cup in the back of the intake body.
  8. install the intake adapter on the other end of the tube and hook to the intake of the pump.
  9. install the outlet body on another length of tube.
  10. take two cover nuts and the outlet lid and fasten the lid down medium tight.
  11. install the other end of the tube on the outlet of the pump using the adapter if needed.
  12. (optional) while this was designed to be a submerged in tank system you can use extra long vinyl tubing and wrap excess tubing around a uv light it will kill bacteria in the water helping it to clear faster. but be sure not to expose your filter media to the UV radiation as it will kill helpful bacteria as well. also for the same reason you don't want to use this method on a tank that isn't established.

I have a 200gph pump on it and the intake doesn't create much current (safer for fish) the exit generates a nice gentle current the guppies seem to love.

comments.text: still using this. does an excellent job and cool thing is I can see clearly in the side when the quilt batting needs to be changed. I don't use the outlet anymore it's just too much bulk for a small tank. I'll probably make a smaller one that focuses the current a bit more.

Recommend using PETG as it has proven to be strong, rigid, yet flexible to allow "spring" parts to function for a long time. PETG

I DO NOT recommend PLA as it will quickly fail from flexing.

ABS will probably work Ok, but I have not tried it. As the print has a large, relatively thin, flat area - ABS may be subject to warping depending on your printer and setting.

Tinkercad - with literally about 15 minutes from starting the design to printing the working model. Amazingly, I did not end up doing any test prints or modifications. LOL!!

I measured the outside diameter of the top and bottom of the controller. I made two circles taking into account the measurements from the controller. I then overlapped the circles to set the overall height to just slightly more than controller. A rectangle forms each of the 4 supports, with the two supports on the side having a half circle attached to function is the tabs to lock the controller in place.

The controller will push straight in, slide in from the bottom, etc. To remove itt pull the bottom of the controller out and slide down. Or give the controller a slight twist as you pull, just play with it and find what works best for you. :)

BTW, Pulling straight down generally results in the controller popping out, but may break the lower retaining tabs. Overall, Im please for such a quick and simple design.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
One of my colleagues is studying diatoms in lakes in Antarctica. However, normally sampling diatoms involves getting wet, which is not terribly fun in Antarctic conditions. To get around this, we developed this sampler, allowing users to scrub and siphon diatoms from almost 1m below the surface, without coming in contact with the water.

In terms of hardware, it's quite cheap to make, requiring a handful of m3x20mm bolts, and 2 m5 x 75mm bolts. Stainless steel hardware is recommended. The poles are extruded aluminium poles of 16 and 25mm external diameter and 1m in length. It uses standard 50ml syringes with a centred nozzle.

This is just the first prototype, and there is a big list of improvements to be incorporated into future versions. In particular:
• Overall size to be decreased - to make it easy to transport. Currently the outer diameter is ~125mm, which makes it difficult to make a protective tube for transport. Ideally I'd like to get the diameter down to ~90mm, so it can fit into a PVC tube. It will also cut down on plastic required
• Syringe inlet to have improved access for cleaning and to make sure it is free of obstructions.
• Toothbrush clamps to be more adaptable. Current design limits the width of the toothbrush and doesn't fit very angled toothbrushes very well.
• Use a rubber seal with a mechanical attachment, rather than glued foam.
• An outlet so that the sample doesn't flow back out through the base of the shield in a haphazard fashion when the syringe is depressed.
• An tool free way to replace the syringe.

To build:
• Print all the components, (print 2 of the pole clamps and of each toothbrush clamp).
• Trim around 80mm from the 25mm aluminium pole. You'll need to fine tune this measurement if you want the scrubber handle locking pin to lock into place.
• Clamp the outer shield and pole clamps and slide the gasket onto the 25mm pole.
• Clamp the scrubber onto the 16mm pole
• Clamp they syringe clamp onto the other 16mm pole
• Attach the other syringe clamp to the outer shield with the m5 bolts.
• Slide the poles together, and clamp the scrubber handle to the top of the scrubber, and the syringe handle to the top of the syringe pole. You may need to fine tune the handle position if you want the locking pin to fit.
• Bolt the toothbrush clamps with the open ends outwards. Slide some toothbrushes in and tighten the clamps.
• Glue some foam to the base of the shield so that it can seal against the rock.
Note: Some sanding may be required as some of the components are quite tight tolerances.

To use:
• Release the locking pin on the scrubber handle.
• Stick the sampler up against an underwater rock.
• Push the scrubber handle down until the toothbrushes contact the rock.
• Scrub, scrub, scrub.
• Pull up the handle and engage the locking pin.
• Pull up the syringe handle to capture your sample.

title: Piezo Z-Sense Mount for Prusa/Anet style printers

description.text:
This version is depreciated

Find the new version here

I bring you: The Universal Piezo Z-Sensing Extruder Mount!

This Thing is a replacement X-Carriage extruder mount that incorporates the Precision Piezo sensor. It allows the printer to get pinpoint accurate Z-Axis offsets without any compromise.

Included in this thing are mounts for the original Precision Piezo, and two different mounting styles for my own PCB design that comes with several print head enhancements, which include:

  • Flat Flexible cable for transporting all signal and voltage for the cleanest possible cable chain.
  • Onboard voltage regulators allowing use of either 5v or 12v DC fans regardless of Vcc (PWM control still works)
  • LED's on all controlled traces for visual feedback

So what's it do?
this is a replacement for all z-probes, endstops, and other methods for detecting z-min. In simple terms, we're sandwiching a ceramic disk in between the extruder mount, that, when the nozzle touches the bed, sends a z-trig signal.

How does it work?
When a Piezoelectric disk is compressed, or flexed, it sends out a ripple of voltage. When the nozzle touches the bed, the entire extruder is imperceptibly pushed upward, causing torsion on the X-Carriage. Since we mount the Piezo disk in between the extruder and the X-Carriage, the disk flexes into the small cavity left behind it when the nozzle touches the bed. This in turn causes a voltage ripple, which is sent through an array of voltage comparators in the Precision Piezo circuit, which in turn then send the z-trigger signal wen the voltage ripple hits a certain threshold.

How is this better than z-probes like inductive sensors, or the BLTouch?
All of these methods, endstops, and z-probes, operate under referential circumstances. They are unfortunately prone to issues when things like the mounts are not secure, or your extruder's nozzle is changed, or any number of other factors. The Piezo Z-Sensor, on the other hand, has several advantages that eliminate most of the headaches of these other methods:

  • Uses the nozzle itself to sense, therefore there's no X/Y offsets
  • If swapping nozzles, or using a modular print head, the z-sensor is uneffected, as it works from within the mount. No need to re-adjust z-offsets
  • Extremely high accuracy and repeatability. the original developer claims 0.01mm accuracy
  • No deadzones when probing the bed - probe anywhere you can print
  • Works on ANY print surface

Where can I get one of these sensors!?
The original developer has an online shop where several different versions can be purchased. My own version is currently in validation testing, but if there's enough interest I could put a large batch together. Currently I'm doing them by hand so if you'd like one, just shoot me a message and we'll work something out.

A big thank you to all the people who helped develop the Piezo Z-Sensor in the first place, Nial Brekke, Mike Simpson, Idris Nowell, and DjDemonD for bringing this project over to Thingiverse!

I'm in the middle of re-printing part of my extruder but once that's complete I can test the sensor more thoroughly. The tests look very promising so far though. The only major I issue I can see coming up is vibrations from the machine causing false-positive triggers, but that's what the adjustment trim-pots are for.
comments.author: Freakadude

comments.text: Regarding vibrations and false positives. Don't know what setup you have running on your machine but i use Ramps with Marlin and for that following things were suggested elsewhere to neutralize this potential effect. In Marlin config use: #define DELAY_BEFORE_PROBING 400 ; Before each Z probe move the software waits 400 ms before doing the Z movement. This in theory neutralizes any remainder ringing in the setup that may cause false positives.
